<p><B>Course goals and learning outcomes:  </B>These days, everybody has to make decisions about computer systems and information technology. What computer or cellphone should you (or your company) buy? Whom should you hire to design your web site or to set up a network for your business? What precautions should you take before doing online banking from your cellphone or posting pictures on Facebook? How do you decide which way to vote on ballot propositions that relate to the internet?</P>
<p>Because technology changes rapidly, the best answers to these questions won't be the same next year as they are today. Your best strategy for making good decisions over the longer term is to know not just the current details but the underlying concepts of computing; they'll have a longer &quot;shelf life.&quot; 
This course looks &quot;under the hood&quot; at modern computing systems, not because most students will become computer professionals and have careers working under the hood, but because gaining some concrete knowledge about how computers work is the best way to learn those underlying, long-shelf-life concepts.</P>
<P>
  <B>Prerequisite courses and concepts:</B>
  This course was designed for majors outside of the School of Information and Computer Sciences; it has no academic prerequisites.   We do expect you to have these basic
  computing skills:  Searching and browsing the Web, reading and sending Email,
  downloading files, viewing and printing PDF (Adobe Acrobat) documents, creating simple documents in a conventional word processor (like Word or Pages or NeoOffice or Google Docs), and
  creating or saving documents for Email and other purposes in plain ASCII
text form (not HTML or Word attachments). If you need to brush up on any of these, let us know and we'll help. </P>
<P>
<B>Meeting place and times:</B>  Lecture meets
Tuesdays and Thursdays from 12:30 to 2:00 p.m. in Humanities Hall 178.</P>
<P><!--We're meeting in this room because class sessions are being recorded for possible use in a future online class. -->The computer screen and audio of each class will be recorded and available through UCI Replay; after each class, you will receive electronic mail with the link for access. <!--But capture of the whiteboard and document projector are still experimental and require post-production; you shouldn't count on their being available this quarter.--> The UCI Replay process is not 100% reliable; some classes may end up not being recorded and classes where we use the whiteboard or overhead projector will not have those visuals captured at all. Practically, this means you should plan to attend class in person and not count on recordings  being available. UCI Replay recordings are good as a backup, but they're no substitute for regular in-person attendance.</P>
<P><strong>Lab hours:</strong> The TA wil schedule optional office/lab hours as needed for each assignment; stay tuned to your Email for days and times. These will probably be held in the ICS Open Lab, ICS 364.</P>
<P><strong>Special sections:</strong> Special assistants Debra Richardson and Amelia Regan are developing a variety of activities that convey ICS 10 topics interactively. Starting April 5, they will lead a special section for these activities every Tuesday afternoon from 5:00 to 6:50 p.m. in Social Ecology 101.</P>
<P>These special sections are optional: There are no &quot;course points&quot; specifically tied to your attendance and you may attend some weeks and not others. But it's likely that spending a little more time focusing on the course material will enhance your understanding and lead to higher scores. And besides, it should be a lot of fun!</P>
<P>
<B>Office hours:</B>  You are welcome to drop by my office at any time. If I'm there and not immersed in something else, I'll be glad to chat about the course material or other topics. I will definitely be in or near my office Thursdays from 2:45 to 3:15, <!---during these scheduled hours,--> during which course-related matters will have first priority.<!--: Tuesdays from 11:30 to 12:15 and Thursdays after class.--> I may adjust these times at the end of the first week. Of course emergencies may come up, but I will try to give advance notice of any change. I'll also be happy to make arrangements for other times during the week; &quot;making an appointment&quot; is no big deal (but if you make one, don't skip it without getting in touch).
